he West in its true Mediterranean context. Her inquiry centers on the notion of "Christendom." Instead of taking medieval beliefs for granted or separating theology from politics, she treats the faith as a material force. In a path-breaking account of the arguments over Christian doctrine, she shows how the northern sphere of the Roman world divided into two distinct and self-conscious imperial units, as the Arabs swept through the southern regions. One of the most interesting strands of the author's argument concerns religious art and iconoclasm. Her book shows how the impact of Islam's Judaic ban on graven images precipitated both the iconoclast crisis in Constantinople and the West's unique commitment to pictorial narrative, as justified by Pope Gregory the Great.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAbedrapsas.  aAesclepius.  aAetios.  aBannbanaus.  aEgypt.  aEucharist.  aEuprepios.  aGeorge (iconophile monk).  aGermanos.  aGussinus (Gothic nobleman).  aHatfield, council of.  aHuns.  aIncarnation of God as Man.  aJames the deacon.  aJohn of Jerusalem.  aKaaba.  aKhirbat al Minya.  aLaidcenn.  aLakedaimonia.  aMaastricht.  aManichaeanism.  aMaximos the Confessor.  aNew Jerusalem.  aNew Testament.  aNorthumbria.  aPalestine.  aPeter the patrician.  aQuintus Serenus.  aReformation.  aReno.  aSaragossa.  aSarapion the Sindonite.  aSong of Roland.  aSquillace.  aTheodore of Koloneia.  aTheudemir.  aTrinitarian problems.  aUmayyad dynasty.  aUtrecht (map 3).  aVitaliani.  aVulgate.  aYarmuk River.  aZoroastrianism.  aforgery.  aicons of Christ.  aoikoumene.  apaganism.  apapyrus.  arhetoric.  asacellarius.  atranslation.  avia regis.  avoluntas.  a